## B. Measurement Model

At a certain moment, the LiDAR acquires $m$ sampling points $\left\{\boldsymbol{p}_{j}\right\}_{j=1}^{m}$. Each point $\boldsymbol{p}_{j}$ transformed into the word coordinate system is denoted as $\boldsymbol{p}_{j}^{w}:=(\boldsymbol{K} \Gamma(\boldsymbol{T})) * \boldsymbol{p}_{j}$, where $*$ represents a group action of $\operatorname{SE}(3)$ on $\mathbb{R}^{3}:(A, a) * x:=A x+a$. Search for the five points closest to $\boldsymbol{p}_{j}^{w}$ and fit a plane, then $\boldsymbol{p}_{j}^{w}$ should be in this plane (Fig. 2). Therefore, the system output $h_{j}: \mathcal{M} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ can be configured as [14]

$$
h_{j}(\xi)=\boldsymbol{n}_{j}^{\top}\left(\boldsymbol{p}_{j}^{w}-\boldsymbol{q}_{j}\right)
$$

where $\boldsymbol{n}_{j}$ is the normal vector of the plane and $\boldsymbol{q}_{j}$ is an arbitrary point in the plane.

According to [8], the linearized measurement equation is

$$
\boldsymbol{z}_{j}=\boldsymbol{H}_{j} \varepsilon, \quad \boldsymbol{H}_{j}=\left(d h_{j}\right)_{\hat{\xi}} \circ\left(d \phi_{\hat{X}}\right)_{\xi^{0}} \circ\left(d \varphi^{-1}\right)_{\mathbf{0}}
$$

The closed-form of the matrix $\boldsymbol{H}_{j}$ is

$$
\boldsymbol{H}_{j}=\left[\begin{array}{lll}
\boldsymbol{O}_{1 \times 9} & \boldsymbol{O}_{1 \times 9} & \boldsymbol{H}_{j, K}
\end{array}\right] \in \mathbb{R}^{1 \times 24}
$$

where

$$
\boldsymbol{H}_{j, K}=\left[\begin{array}{ll}
-\boldsymbol{u}_{j}^{\top}\left(\hat{B} * \boldsymbol{p}_{j}^{w}\right)^{\wedge} & \boldsymbol{u}_{j}^{\top}
\end{array}\right] \in \mathbb{R}^{1 \times 6}
$$

## III. Derivation of the State Matrix

For a state $\xi \in \mathcal{M}$, define $e=\phi_{\bar{X}^{-1}}(\xi) \in \mathcal{M}$ as the error on the manifold $\mathcal{M}$. Fix any origin $\xi^{0}=\left(\boldsymbol{T}^{0},\left(\boldsymbol{b}^{0}\right)^{\wedge}, \boldsymbol{K}^{0}\right) \in \mathcal{M}$, which usually represents the origin state at the first frame, we can choose a smooth coordinate map $\varphi: U \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{9} \oplus \mathbb{R}^{9} \oplus \mathbb{R}^{6}$ :

$$
\varphi(e)=\log _{G} \circ\left(\phi^{\left(\xi^{0}\right)}\right)^{-1}(e)
$$

where $\log _{G}$ is the logarithmic map of the Lie group $G$. The state matrix $\boldsymbol{F}$ is be computed by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{F} & =\left(d \varphi\right)_{\xi^{0}} \circ\left(d \phi^{\left(\xi^{0}\right)}\right)_{I} \circ\left(d \Lambda_{\boldsymbol{u}^{0}}\right)_{\xi^{0}} \circ\left(d \varphi^{-1}\right)_{\mathbf{0}} \\
& =\left(d \Lambda_{\boldsymbol{u}^{0}}\right)_{\xi^{0}} \circ\left(d \phi^{\left(\xi^{0}\right)}\right)_{I}
\end{aligned}
$$

where the last equality is derived by substituting the expression of $\varphi$. For $\boldsymbol{u}^{0}=\left(\left(\boldsymbol{w}^{0}\right)^{\wedge},\left(\boldsymbol{g}^{0}\right)^{\wedge}, \mathbf{0}^{\wedge}, \mathbf{0}^{\wedge}\right)$, using Lemma 1.1 and Lemma 1.2, we can compute that

$$
\boldsymbol{F}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\boldsymbol{F}_{T} & \boldsymbol{I}_{9 \times 9} & \boldsymbol{O}_{9 \times 6} \\
\boldsymbol{F}_{b T} & \boldsymbol{F}_{b} & \boldsymbol{O}_{9 \times 6} \\
\boldsymbol{F}_{K T} & \boldsymbol{F}_{K b} & \boldsymbol{F}_{K}
\end{array}\right] \in \mathbb{R}^{24 \times 24}
$$

where

$$
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{F}_{T}= & {\left[\begin{array}{l}
\left(\boldsymbol{C}^{0}\right)^{-1}\left(\boldsymbol{g}^{0}\right)^{0} \\
\left(\left(\boldsymbol{C}^{0}\right)^{-1} \boldsymbol{v}^{0}\right)^{\wedge} \\
\boldsymbol{I}_{3 \times 3}
\end{array}\right]-\operatorname{ad}_{\boldsymbol{b}^{0}}^{\vee} \in \mathbb{R}^{9 \times 9} } \\
\boldsymbol{F}_{b T}= & \operatorname{ad}_{\boldsymbol{b}^{0}}^{\vee} \boldsymbol{F}_{T}-\operatorname{ad}_{\Lambda_{1}\left(\xi^{0}, \boldsymbol{u}^{0}\right)}^{\vee} \operatorname{ad}_{\boldsymbol{b}^{0}}^{\vee} \in \mathbb{R}^{9 \times 9} \\
\boldsymbol{F}_{b}= & \operatorname{ad}_{\Lambda_{1}\left(\xi^{0}, \boldsymbol{u}^{0}\right)}^{\vee}+\operatorname{ad}_{\boldsymbol{b}^{0}}^{\vee} \in \mathbb{R}^{9 \times 9} \\
\boldsymbol{F}_{K T}= & \left(\boldsymbol{I}_{6 \times 6}-\operatorname{ad}_{\operatorname{Ad}_{\left(\boldsymbol{K}^{0}\right)^{-1}} \Gamma \Lambda_{1}\left(\xi^{0}, \boldsymbol{u}^{0}\right)}^{\vee}\right) \\
& \operatorname{Ad}_{\left(\boldsymbol{K}^{0}\right)^{-1}}^{\vee} \Gamma^{\vee} \boldsymbol{F}_{T} \in \mathbb{R}^{6 \times 9} \\
\boldsymbol{F}_{K b}= & \operatorname{Ad}_{\left(\boldsymbol{K}^{0}\right)^{-1}} \Gamma^{\vee} \in \mathbb{R}^{6 \times 9} \\
\boldsymbol{F}_{K}= & \operatorname{ad}_{\left(\operatorname{Ad}_{(\boldsymbol{K}^{0})^{-1}} \Gamma \Lambda\left(\xi^{0}, \boldsymbol{u}^{0}\right)\right)}^{\vee} \in \mathbb{R}^{6 \times 6}
\end{aligned}
$$

with

$$
\Gamma^{\vee}=\left[\begin{array}{lll}
\boldsymbol{I}_{3 \times 3} & \boldsymbol{O}_{3 \times 3} & \boldsymbol{O}_{3 \times 3} \\
\boldsymbol{O}_{3 \times 3} & \boldsymbol{O}_{3 \times 3} & \boldsymbol{I}_{3 \times 3}
\end{array}\right] \in \mathbb{R}^{6 \times 9}
$$

and

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \Lambda_{1}\left(\xi^{0}, \boldsymbol{u}^{0}\right) \\
& =\left(\boldsymbol{w}^{0}\right)^{\wedge}-\left(\boldsymbol{b}^{0}\right)^{\wedge}+\operatorname{Ad}_{\left(\boldsymbol{T}^{0}\right)^{-1}}\left(\boldsymbol{g}^{0}\right)^{\wedge}+\left(\boldsymbol{T}^{0}\right)^{-1} f_{1}^{0}\left(\boldsymbol{T}^{0}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

The symbol $\Gamma^{\vee}$ is consistent with the definition of $\Gamma$ provided by the main document.

Additionally, we can compute the origin input $\boldsymbol{u}^{0}$ by using Proposition 4.2:

$$
\boldsymbol{w}^{0}=\operatorname{Ad}_{\tilde{A}} \boldsymbol{w}^{\wedge}+f_{1}^{0}(\tilde{A})+\dot{a}^{\wedge}, \boldsymbol{g}^{0}=\boldsymbol{g}
$$

Usually, the system state at the first frame is equal to $\xi^{0}=$ $\left(\boldsymbol{I}_{5 \times 5}, \boldsymbol{O}_{9 \times 9}, \boldsymbol{I}_{4 \times 4}\right)$. In this case, the matrix $\boldsymbol{F}$ is coincident with the equation (10) in the main document.

## IV. Derivation of the Input Matrix

We assume that all the noises are additive Gaussian white noises. According [2], the input matrix $\boldsymbol{B}$ can be computed by

$$
\boldsymbol{B}=d \varphi_{\xi^{\circ}} \circ\left(d \phi^{\left(\xi^{0}\right)}\right)_{I} \circ \operatorname{Ad}_{\tilde{X}} \circ d\left(\Lambda_{\tilde{\xi}}\right)_{\boldsymbol{u}}
$$

Since $\varphi$ is defined by equation (2), we have

$$
\boldsymbol{B}=\operatorname{Ad}_{\tilde{X}} \circ d\left(\Lambda_{\tilde{\xi}}\right)_{\boldsymbol{u}}
$$

where $\boldsymbol{u}=\left(\boldsymbol{w}^{\wedge}, \boldsymbol{g}^{\wedge}, \mathbf{0}^{\wedge}, \mathbf{0}^{\wedge}\right)$ is the current input. We only consider the noises of the IMU measurements $\boldsymbol{w}$ and the biases b. It is easy to compute that

$$
d\left(\Lambda_{\tilde{\xi}}\right)_{\boldsymbol{u}}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\boldsymbol{I}_{9 \times 9} & \boldsymbol{O}_{9 \times 9} \\
\operatorname{ad}_{\tilde{\boldsymbol{K}}}^{\vee} & -\boldsymbol{I}_{9 \times 9} \\
\operatorname{Ad}_{\tilde{\boldsymbol{K}}}^{\vee \vee} \Gamma^{\vee} & \boldsymbol{O}_{9 \times 9}
\end{array}\right] \in \mathbb{R}^{24 \times 18}
$$

Since

$$
\operatorname{Ad}_{\tilde{X}}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\operatorname{Ad}_{\tilde{A}}^{\vee} & \\
\operatorname{ad}_{\tilde{\tilde{A}}}^{\vee} \operatorname{Ad}_{\tilde{A}}^{\vee} & \operatorname{Ad}_{\tilde{A}}^{\vee} \\
\operatorname{Ad}_{\left(\boldsymbol{K}^{0}\right)^{-1} \Gamma(\tilde{A})}^{\vee} & \boldsymbol{A}^{\vee}
\end{array}\right]_{B}^{\vee}
$$

the expression of $\boldsymbol{B}$ is

$$
\boldsymbol{B}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\operatorname{Ad}_{\tilde{A}}^{\vee} \\
\operatorname{ad}_{\tilde{\boldsymbol{k}}^{0}}^{\vee} \operatorname{Ad}_{\tilde{A}}^{\vee} \\
\operatorname{Ad}_{\left(\boldsymbol{K}^{0}\right)^{-1} \Gamma(\tilde{A})}^{\vee} \Gamma^{\vee}
\end{array}-\operatorname{Ad}_{\tilde{A}}^{\vee}\right] \in \mathbb{R}^{24 \times 18}
$$
